  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The Pope is always a man because of longstanding traditions and interpretations of Catholic doctrine. The role of the Pope, as the Bishop of Rome and the leader of the worldwide Catholic Church, has traditionally been filled by men, based on the precedent set by Jesus Christ and his apostles. \n\nCatholic teaching holds that Jesus appointed only men as his apostles, and these apostles were the first leaders of the early Church. This tradition has been maintained over the centuries, and the Church has continued to ordain only men to the priesthood and episcopacy, which includes the office of the Pope.\n\nAdditionally, the Catholic Church teaches that the priest, when celebrating the Eucharist, acts in the person of Christ (\"in persona Christi\"). Since Christ was male, the Church has maintained that only men can fulfill this role.\n\nThese teachings and traditions have been reaffirmed by various Church documents and statements from Popes and Church councils over the years. While there are discussions and differing opinions within and outside the Church regarding the ordination of women, the official stance of the Catholic Church remains that only men can be ordained as priests and bishops, and therefore only men can become Pope.",
